  "exemplar_id": "ex_epistaxis_001",
  "frozen": true,
  "context_summary": "55-year-old woman arrives with an actively bleeding nose that started 20 minutes ago while she was blowing her nose. She has been pinching the soft part of her nose and leaning forward as instructed, but bleeding continues. No history of trauma. The doctor is deciding whether this is a straightforward anterior bleed manageable with pressure and topical vasoconstrictor versus a posterior bleed that needs escalation.",
  "good_next_question": "Which side did the bleeding start on, and even with your head tilted forward and pressure on, are you still feeling or tasting blood running down the back of your throat?",
  "rationale": "Distinguishing an anterior bleed, usually unilateral and originating from Kiesselbach's plexus, from a posterior bleed, often less clearly lateralized and continuing to drain down the throat despite proper forward-leaning pressure, determines the entire management pathway. Anterior bleeds typically respond to direct pressure, topical vasoconstrictors, or anterior packing, while posterior bleeds carry a higher risk of significant blood loss and airway compromise, often fail simple anterior measures, and may require posterior packing, balloon tamponade, or ENT and interventional radiology involvement. Persistent throat drainage despite correct first-aid positioning is the specific red flag that a posterior source is likely. Asking only about the volume of bleeding is a weaker discriminator, since it flags hemodynamic risk but doesn't localize the source the way the throat-drainage question does.",
  "tags": [
    "ent",
    "epistaxis",
    "nosebleed",
    "adult",
    "anterior_vs_posterior"
  ],
